SIMPLE: sympathize
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sympathize
<hw>Sym"pa*thize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Sympathized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Sympathizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>sympathiser</ets>. See <er>Sympathy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To have a common feeling, as of bodily pleasure or pain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mind will <qex>sympathize</qex> so much with the anguish and
debility of the body, that it will be too distracted to fix itself in
meditation.</q> <rj><qau>Buckminster.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To feel in consequence of what another feels; to be
affected by feelings similar to those of another, in consequence of
knowing the person to be thus affected.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their countrymen . . . <qex>sympathized</qex> with their heroes in
all their adventures.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To agree; to be in accord; to harmonize.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sympathize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sympathize
<hw>Sym"pa*thize</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To experience
together.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧This <xex>sympathized</xex> .
. . error.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To ansew to; to correspond to.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sympathizer</ent>⟦br⟧
